Technological determinism is a term that in practice covers a wide range of ideas about the so-called technological thrust, i.e. the need for technology, to such an absolute perception that human nature is guided by the logic based on scientific laws and their expression in technology.
Most interpretations of technological determinism have two basic principles: first, that technological development itself follows a path that is largely beyond cultural and political influence, and secondly, that technology in turn has inherent, rather than socially conditioned, “impacts” on societies.
As an example, could claim that the invention of a car inevitably leads to the development of roads.
On the other hand, a national road network is not economically profitable for just a few cars, so new production methods are being developed to lower the cost of owning a car.
The mass ownership of cars results in more accidents in road transport, leading to the invention of new health care methods to repair damaged bodies.
